radsw_datatb.f
1!> \file radsw_datatb.f
2!! This file contains many individual data modules with specifically
3!! precalculated data tables:
4!! - module_radsw_ref (reference temperature and pressure)
5!! - module_radsw_cldprtb (cloud property coefficients table)
6!! - module_radsw_sflux (spectral solar flux distribution)
7!! - module_radsw_kgbnn (absorption coeffients for 14 bands,
8!! where nn = 16-29)
9!\defgroup radsw_datatb GFS RADSW datatb Modules
10!\ingroup RRTMG
11
12! ============================================================== !!!!!
13! sw-rrtm3 radiation package description !!!!!
14! ============================================================== !!!!!
15! !
16! this package includes ncep's modifications of the rrtm-sw radiation !
17! code from aer inc. !
18! !
19! the sw-rrtm3 package includes these parts: !
20! !
21! 'radsw_rrtm3_param.f' !
22! 'radsw_rrtm3_datatb.f' !
23! 'radsw_rrtm3_main.f' !
24! !
25! the 'radsw_rrtm3_param.f' contains: !
26! !
27! 'module_radsw_parameters' -- band parameters set up !
28! !
29! the 'radsw_rrtm3_datatb.f' contains: !
30! !
31! 'module_radsw_ref' -- reference temperature and pressure !
32! 'module_radsw_cldprtb' -- cloud property coefficients table !
33! 'module_radsw_sflux' -- spectral solar flux distribution !
34! 'module_radsw_kgbnn' -- absorption coeffients for 14 !
35! bands, where nn = 16-29 !
36! !
37! the 'radsw_rrtm3_main.f' contains: !
38! !
39! 'rrtmg_sw' -- main sw radiation transfer !
40! !
41! in the main module 'rrtmg_sw' there are only two !
42! externally callable subroutines: !
43! !
44! 'swrad' -- main rrtm3 sw radiation routine !
45! 'rswinit' -- initialization routine !
46! !
47! all the sw radiation subprograms become contained subprograms !
48! in module 'rrtmg_sw' and many of them are not directly !
49! accessable from places outside the module. !
50! !
51! compilation sequence is: !
52! !
53! 'radsw_rrtm3_param.f' !
54! 'radsw_rrtm3_datatb.f' !
55! 'radsw_rrtm3_main.f' !
56! !
57! and all should be put in front of routines that use sw modules !
58! !
59! ncep modifications history log: !
60! !
61! see list in program "radsw_rrtm3_main.f" !
62! !
63!!!!! ============================================================== !!!!!
64!!!!! end descriptions !!!!!
65!!!!! ============================================================== !!!!!

139!> \ingroup module_radsw_main
140!> \brief This module contains cloud radiative property coefficients.
141!!
142!! For liquid water clouds, cloud radiative property coefficients are
143!! derived from \cite hu_and_stamnes_1993.
144!! For ice clouds, there are various choices for model applications,
145!! including data tables derived from
146!! \cite ebert_and_curry_1992, from the Streamer scheme
147!! \cite key_2002, or from \cite fu_1996 . Components of
148!! snow particles and rain droplets are not parameterized in the
149!! operational NEMS/GSM cloud microphysics scheme, and their radiative
150!! properties are neither well established yet. Coefficients for those
151!! components listed in the module are more experimental oriented that
152!! include the entries for snow from Fu (2001, personal communications),
153!! and for rain from \cite chou_and_suarez_1999.
154!!
155!! In common practices, the cloud radiative properties (optical depth,
156!! single scattering albedo, and asymmetry factor) are usually parametized
157!! in the form of a truncated Laurent series (generalized Taylor series)
158!!\f[
159!! f(x)=\sum_{n=-N}^Na_{n}(x-c)^n
160!!\f]
161!! Where \f$x\f$ represents the cloud particle's effective radius (in
162!! Fu's scheme, it is called as generalized size parameter) in unites of
163!! micro-meters, \f$a_{n}\f$ represents the corresponding coefficients,
164!! and the constant \f$c\f$ will be zero. The number of terms, \f$n\f$,
165!! are usually kept small, such as \f$n=0,-1\f$ for the extinction
166!! coefficients and \f$n=0,1,2\f$ (or a bit larger) for the coefficients
167!! of single scattering albedo and asymmetry factor. When using the
168!! Ebert and Curry cloud optical property scheme, cloud optical properties
169!! are computed 'on the fly' by using the power series in five broad
170!! spectral bands (similar expressions are used for Fu's snow and Chou's
171!! rain schemes). While for other schemes, optical properties are
172!! precomputed for each of the 14 RRTMG-SW bands in corresponding to
173!! evenly distributed particle effective radius (e.g. 1 or 3 micro-meter
174!! intervals for water or ice clouds, respectively). Simple linear
175!! interpolations will be used during radiative transfer calculations.
176 module module_radsw_cldprtb !
177!........................................!
178!
179! *********************** module descriptions ********************** !
180! !
181! this module contains coefficients of cloud-optical properties !
182! for each of the spectral bands. modified from aer/ecmwf rrtm !
183! sw radiation package subroutine "susrtop". !
184! !
185! modify history: !
186! jan 2004 -- yu-tai hou convert subroutine to data !
187! module for ncep models. !
188! jun 2008 -- yu-tai hou modified to use aer's newer !
189! release v3.5 data table for cloud ice particles !
190! jun 2018 -- h-m lin/y-t hou updated with aer's newer !
191! version of v3.9-v4.0 liq cloud optical property !
192! coeffs for hu and stamnes scheme !
193! !
194! ********* the original program descriptions ********* !
195! !
196! adapted from j. delamere, atmospheric & environmental research. !
197! by jjmorcrette, ecmwf 02/10/29 !
198! revision: j.d. 2.6 2002/04/04 18:29:47 !
199! reformatted for f90 by jjmorcrette, ecmwf !
200! !
201! name type purpose
202! ---- : ---- : --------------------------------------------------!
203! xxxliq1 : real : optical properties (extinction coefficient, single!
204! xxxliq2 (updated) scattering albedo, assymetry factor) from !
205! hu & stamnes, 1993, j. clim., 6, 728-742 !
206! xbari : real : optical properties (extinction coefficient, single!
207! scattering albedo, assymetry factor) calculated !
208! based on ebert and curry method, jgr, 1992 !
209! xxxice2 : real : optical properties (extinction coefficient, single!
210! scattering albedo, assymetry factor) from !
211! streamer v3.0, key.j.streamer user's guide, !
212! cooperative institute for meteorological satellite!
213! studies, 2001, 96 pp. !
214! xxxice3 : real : optical properties (extinction coefficient, single!
215! scattering albedo, assymetry factor) from !
216! fu, 1996, j. clim., 9, !
217! !
218! ************************* end description ************************ !

2859!> the array selfref contains the coefficient of the water vapor
2860!! self-continuum (including the energy term). the first index
2861!! refers to temperature in 7.2 degree increments. for instance,
2862!! jt = 1 refers to a temperature of 245.6, jt = 2 refers to 252.8,
2863!! etc. the second index runs over the g-channel (1 to 6).
2864 real (kind=kind_phys), public :: selfref(msf16,ng16)
2865
2866!> the array absa(585,NG16) (ka(9,5,13,NG16)) contains absorption coefs at
2867!! the 16 chosen g-values for a range of pressure levels> ~100mb,
2868!! temperatures, and binary species parameters (see taumol.f for definition).
2869!! the first index in the array, js, runs from 1 to 9, and corresponds
2870!! to different values of the binary species parameter. for instance,
2871!! js=1 refers to dry air, js = 2 corresponds to the paramter value 1/8,
2872!! js = 3 corresponds to the parameter value 2/8, etc. the second index
2873!! in the array, jt, which runs from 1 to 5, corresponds to different
2874!! temperatures. more specifically, jt = 3 means that the data are for
2875!! the reference temperature tref for this pressure level, jt = 2 refers
2876!! to tref-15, jt = 1 is for tref-30, jt = 4 is for tref+15, and jt = 5
2877!! is for tref+30. the third index, jp, runs from 1 to 13 and refers
2878!! to the jpth reference pressure level (see taumol.f for these levels
2879!! in mb). the fourth index, ig, goes from 1 to 6, and indicates
2880!! which g-interval the absorption coefficients are for.
2881 real (kind=kind_phys), public :: absa(msa16,ng16)
2882
2883!> the array absb(235,6) (kb(5,13:59,6)) contains absorption coefs at
2884!! the 16 chosen g-values for a range of pressure levels < ~100mb and
2885!! temperatures. the first index in the array, jt, which runs from 1 to 5,
2886!! corresponds to different temperatures. more specifically, jt = 3 means
2887!! that the data are for the reference temperature tref for this pressure
2888!! level, jt = 2 refers to the temperature tref-15, jt = 1 is for
2889!! tref-30, jt = 4 is for tref+15, and jt = 5 is for tref+30.
2890!! the second index, jp, runs from 13 to 59 and refers to the jpth
2891!! reference pressure level (see taumol.f for the value of these
2892!! pressure levels in mb). the third index, ig, goes from 1 to 6,
2893!! and tells us which g-interval the absorption coefficients are for.
2894 real (kind=kind_phys), public :: absb(msb16,ng16)
2895
2896 real (kind=kind_phys), public :: forref(mfr16,ng16)

3666
3667! the array absb(235,6) (kb(5,13:59,6)) contains absorption coefs at
3668! the 16 chosen g-values for a range of pressure levels < ~100mb and
3669! temperatures. the first index in the array, jt, which runs from 1 to 5,
3670! corresponds to different temperatures. more specifically, jt = 3 means
3671! that the data are for the reference temperature tref for this pressure
3672! level, jt = 2 refers to the temperature tref-15, jt = 1 is for
3673! tref-30, jt = 4 is for tref+15, and jt = 5 is for tref+30.
3674! the second index, jp, runs from 13 to 59 and refers to the jpth
3675! reference pressure level (see taumol.f for the value of these
3676! pressure levels in mb). the third index, ig, goes from 1 to 6,
3677! and tells us which g-interval the absorption coefficients are for.
3678! -----------------------------------------------------------------

4051
4052!> the array selfref contains the coefficient of the water vapor
4053!! self-continuum (including the energy term). the first index
4054!! refers to temperature in 7.2 degree increments. for instance,
4055!! jt = 1 refers to a temperature of 245.6, jt = 2 refers to 252.8,
4056!! etc. the second index runs over the g-channel (1 to NG17).
4057 real (kind=kind_phys), public :: selfref(msf17,ng17)
4058
4059!> the array absa(585,NG17) (ka((9,5,13,NG17)) contains absorption coefs at
4060!! the 16 chosen g-values for a range of pressure levels> ~100mb,
4061!! temperatures, and binary species parameters (see taumol.f for definition).
4062!! the first index in the array, js, runs from 1 to 9, and corresponds to
4063!! different values of the binary species parameter. for instance,
4064!! js=1 refers to dry air, js = 2 corresponds to the paramter value 1/8,
4065!! js = 3 corresponds to the parameter value 2/8, etc. the second index
4066!! in the array, jt, which runs from 1 to 5, corresponds to different
4067!! temperatures. more specifically, jt = 3 means that the data are for
4068!! the reference temperature tref for this pressure level, jt = 2 refers
4069!! to tref-15, jt = 1 is for tref-30, jt = 4 is for tref+15, and jt = 5
4070!! is for tref+30. the third index, jp, runs from 1 to 13 and refers
4071!! to the jpth reference pressure level (see taumol.f for these levels
4072!! in mb). the fourth index, ig, goes from 1 to 12, and indicates
4073!! which g-interval the absorption coefficients are for.
4074 real (kind=kind_phys), public :: absa(msa17,ng17)
4075
4076!> the array absb(1175,12) (kb(5,5,13:59,12)) contains absorption coefs at
4077!! the 16 chosen g-values for a range of pressure levels < ~100mb and
4078!! temperatures. the first index in the array, jt, which runs from 1 to 5,
4079!! corresponds to different temperatures. more specifically, jt = 3 means
4080!! that the data are for the reference temperature tref for this pressure
4081!! level, jt = 2 refers to the temperature tref-15, jt = 1 is for
4082!! tref-30, jt = 4 is for tref+15, and jt = 5 is for tref+30.
4083!! the second index, jp, runs from 13 to 59 and refers to the jpth
4084!! reference pressure level (see taumol.f for the value of these
4085!! pressure levels in mb). the third index, ig, goes from 1 to 12,
4086!! and tells us which g-interval the absorption coefficients are for.
4087 real (kind=kind_phys), public :: absb(msb17,ng17)
4088
4089 real (kind=kind_phys), public :: forref(mfr17,ng17)

8661!> the array selfref contains the coefficient of the water vapor
8662!! self-continuum (including the energy term). the first index
8663!! refers to temperature in 7.2 degree increments. for instance,
8664!! jt = 1 refers to a temperature of 245.6, jt = 2 refers to 252.8,
8665!! etc. the second index runs over the g-channel (1 to 8).
8666 real (kind=kind_phys), public :: selfref(msf18,ng18)
8667
8668!> the array absa(585,NG18) (ka(9,5,13,NG18)) contains absorption coefs at
8669!! the 16 chosen g-values for a range of pressure levels> ~100mb,
8670!! temperatures, and binary species parameters (see taumol.f for definition).
8671!! the first index in the array, js, runs from 1 to 9, and corresponds
8672!! to different values of the binary species parameter. for instance,
8673!! js=1 refers to dry air, js = 2 corresponds to the paramter value 1/8,
8674!! js = 3 corresponds to the parameter value 2/8, etc. the second index
8675!! in the array, jt, which runs from 1 to 5, corresponds to different
8676!! temperatures. more specifically, Jt = 3 means that the data are for
8677!! the reference temperature tref for this pressure level, jt = 2 refers
8678!! to tref-15, jt = 1 is for tref-30, jt = 4 is for tref+15, and jt = 5
8679!! is for tref+30. the third index, jp, runs from 1 to 13 and refers
8680!! to the jpth reference pressure level (see taumol.f for these levels
8681!! in mb). the fourth index, ig, goes from 1 to 8, and indicates
8682!! which g-interval the absorption coefficients are for.
8683 real (kind=kind_phys), public :: absa(msa18,ng18)
8684
8685!> the array absb(235,8) (kb(5,13:59,8)) contains absorption coefs at
8686!! the 16 chosen g-values for a range of pressure levels < ~100mb and
8687!! temperatures. the first index in the array, jt, which runs from 1 to 5,
8688!! corresponds to different temperatures. more specifically, jt = 3 means
8689!! that the data are for the reference temperature tref for this pressure
8690!! level, jt = 2 refers to the temperature tref-15, jt = 1 is for
8691!! tref-30, jt = 4 is for tref+15, and jt = 5 is for tref+30.
8692!! the second index, jp, runs from 13 to 59 and refers to the jpth
8693!! reference pressure level (see taumol.f for the value of these
8694!! pressure levels in mb). the third index, ig, goes from 1 to 8,
8695!! and tells us which g-interval the absorption coefficients are for.
8696 real (kind=kind_phys), public :: absb(msb18,ng18)

10178
10179!> the array selfref contains the coefficient of the water vapor
10180!! self-continuum (including the energy term). the first index
10181!! refers to temperature in 7.2 degree increments. for instance,
10182!! jt = 1 refers to a temperature of 245.6, jt = 2 refers to 252.8,
10183!! etc. the second index runs over the g-channel (1 to 8).
10184 real (kind=kind_phys), public :: selfref(msf19,ng19)
10185
10186!> the array absa(585,NG19) (ka(9,5,13,NG19)) contains absorption coefs at
10187!! the 16 chosen g-values for a range of pressure levels> ~100mb,
10188!! temperatures, and binary species parameters (see taumol.f for definition).
10189!! the first index in the array, js, runs from 1 to 9, and corresponds to
10190!! different values of the binary species parameter. for instance,
10191!! js=1 refers to dry air, js = 2 corresponds to the paramter value 1/8,
10192!! js = 3 corresponds to the parameter value 2/8, etc. the second index
10193!! in the array, jt, which runs from 1 to 5, corresponds to different
10194!! temperatures. more specifically, jt = 3 means that the data are for
10195!! the reference temperature tref for this pressure level, jt = 2 refers
10196!! to tref-15, jt = 1 is for tref-30, jt = 4 is for tref+15, and jt = 5
10197!! is for tref+30. the third index, jp, runs from 1 to 13 and refers
10198!! to the jpth reference pressure level (see taumol.f for these levels
10199!! in mb). the fourth index, ig, goes from 1 to 8, and indicates
10200!! which g-interval the absorption coefficients are for.
10201 real (kind=kind_phys), public :: absa(msa19,ng19)
10202
10203!> the array absb(235,8) (kb(5,13:59,8)) contains absorption coefs at
10204!! the 16 chosen g-values for a range of pressure levels < ~100mb and
10205!! temperatures. the first index in the array, jt, which runs from 1 to 5,
10206!! corresponds to different temperatures. more specifically, jt = 3 means
10207!! that the data are for the reference temperature tref for this pressure
10208!! level, jt = 2 refers to the temperature tref-15, jt = 1 is for
10209!! tref-30, jt = 4 is for tref+15, and jt = 5 is for tref+30.
10210!! the second index, jp, runs from 13 to 59 and refers to the jpth
10211!! reference pressure level (see taumol.f for the value of these
10212!! pressure levels in mb). the third index, ig, goes from 1 to 8,
10213!! and tells us which g-interval the absorption coefficients are for.
10214 real (kind=kind_phys), public :: absb(msb19,ng19)

11702
11703!> the array absa(65,NG20) (ka(5,13,NG20)) contains absorption coefs at
11704!! the 16 chosen g-values for a range of pressure levels> ~100mb,
11705!! temperatures, and binary species parameters (see taumol.f for definition).
11706!! the first index in the array, js, runs from 1 to 9, and corresponds to
11707!! different values of the binary species parameter. for instance,
11708!! js=1 refers to dry air, js = 2 corresponds to the paramter value 1/8,
11709!! js = 3 corresponds to the parameter value 2/8, etc. the second index
11710!! in the array, jt, which runs from 1 to 5, corresponds to different
11711!! temperatures. more specifically, jt = 3 means that the data are for
11712!! the reference temperature tref for this pressure level, jt = 2 refers
11713!! to tref-15, jt = 1 is for tref-30, jt = 4 is for tref+15, and jt = 5
11714!! is for tref+30. the third index, jp, runs from 1 to 13 and refers
11715!! to the jpth reference pressure level (see taumol.f for these levels
11716!! in mb). the fourth index, ig, goes from 1 to 10, and indicates
11717!! which g-interval the absorption coefficients are for.
11718 real (kind=kind_phys), public :: absa(msa20,ng20)
11719
11720!> the array absb(235,10) (kb(5,13:59,10)) contains absorption coefs at
11721!! the 16 chosen g-values for a range of pressure levels < ~100mb and
11722!! temperatures. the first index in the array, jt, which runs from 1 to 5,
11723!! corresponds to different temperatures. more specifically, jt = 3 means
11724!! that the data are for the reference temperature tref for this pressure
11725!! level, jt = 2 refers to the temperature tref-15, jt = 1 is for
11726!! tref-30, jt = 4 is for tref+15, and jt = 5 is for tref+30.
11727!! the second index, jp, runs from 13 to 59 and refers to the jpth
11728!! reference pressure level (see taumol.f for the value of these
11729!! pressure levels in mb). the third index, ig, goes from 1 to 10,
11730!! and tells us which g-interval the absorption coefficients are for.
11731 real (kind=kind_phys), public :: absb(msb20,ng20)
11732
11733!> the array selfref contains the coefficient of the water vapor
11734!! self-continuum (including the energy term). the first index
11735!! refers to temperature in 7.2 degree increments. For instance,
11736!! jt = 1 refers to a temperature of 245.6, jt = 2 refers to 252.8,
11737!! etc. the second index runs over the g-channel (1 to 10).
11738 real (kind=kind_phys), public :: selfref(msf20,ng20)

12483
12484!> the array absa(585,NG21) (ka((9,5,13,NG21)) contains absorption coefs at
12485!! the 16 chosen g-values for a range of pressure levels> ~100mb,
12486!! temperatures, and binary species parameters (see taumol.f for definition).
12487!! the first index in the array, js, runs from 1 to 9, and corresponds to
12488!! different values of the binary species parameter. for instance,
12489!! js=1 refers to dry air, js = 2 corresponds to the paramter value 1/8,
12490!! js = 3 corresponds to the parameter value 2/8, etc. the second index
12491!! in the array, jt, which runs from 1 to 5, corresponds to different
12492!! temperatures. more specifically, jt = 3 means that the data are for
12493!! the reference temperature tref for this pressure level, jt = 2 refers
12494!! to tref-15, jt = 1 is for tref-30, jt = 4 is for tref+15, and jt = 5
12495!! is for tref+30. the third index, jp, runs from 1 to 13 and refers
12496!! to the jpth reference pressure level (see taumol.f for these levels
12497!! in mb). the fourth index, ig, goes from 1 to 10, and indicates
12498!! which g-interval the absorption coefficients are for.
12499 real (kind=kind_phys), public :: absa(msa21,ng21)
12500
12501!> the array absb(1175,10) (kb(5,5,13:59,10)) contains absorption coefs at
12502!! the 16 chosen g-values for a range of pressure levels < ~100mb and
12503!! temperatures. the first index in the array, jt, which runs from 1 to 5,
12504!! corresponds to different temperatures. more specifically, jt = 3 means
12505!! that the data are for the reference temperature tref for this pressure
12506!! level, jt = 2 refers to the temperature tref-15, jt = 1 is for
12507!! tref-30, jt = 4 is for tref+15, and jt = 5 is for tref+30.
12508!! the second index, jp, runs from 13 to 59 and refers to the jpth
12509!! reference pressure level (see taumol.f for the value of these
12510!! pressure levels in mb). the third index, ig, goes from 1 to 10,
12511!! and tells us which g-interval the absorption coefficients are for.
12512 real (kind=kind_phys), public :: absb(msb21,ng21)
12513
12514!> the array selfref contains the coefficient of the water vapor
12515!! self-continuum (including the energy term). the first index
12516!! refers to temperature in 7.2 degree increments. for instance,
12517!! jt = 1 refers to a temperature of 245.6, jt = 2 refers to 252.8,
12518!! etc. the second index runs over the g-channel (1 to 10).

16340 real (kind=kind_phys), public :: forref(mfr22,ng22)
16341
16342!> the array absa(585,NG22) (ka(9,5,13,NG22)) contains absorption coefs at
16343!! the 16 chosen g-values for a range of pressure levels> ~100mb,
16344!! temperatures, and binary species parameters (see taumol.f for definition).
16345!! the first index in the array, js, runs from 1 to 9, and corresponds to
16346!! different values of the binary species parameter. for instance,
16347!! js=1 refers to dry air, js = 2 corresponds to the paramter value 1/8,
16348!! js = 3 corresponds to the parameter value 2/8, etc. the second index
16349!! in the array, jt, which runs from 1 to 5, corresponds to different
16350!! temperatures. more specifically, jt = 3 means that the data are for
16351!! the reference temperature tref for this pressure level, jt = 2 refers
16352!! to tref-15, jt = 1 is for tref-30, jt = 4 is for tref+15, and jt = 5
16353!! is for tref+30. the third index, jp, runs from 1 to 13 and refers
16354!! to the jpth reference pressure level (see taumol.f for these levels
16355!! in mb). the fourth index, ig, goes from 1 to 2, and indicates
16356!! which g-interval the absorption coefficients are for.
16357 real (kind=kind_phys), public :: absa(msa22,ng22)
16358
16359!> the array absb(235,2) (kb(5,13:59,2)) contains absorption coefs at
16360!! the 16 chosen g-values for a range of pressure levels < ~100mb and
16361!! temperatures. the first index in the array, jt, which runs from 1 to 5,
16362!! corresponds to different temperatures. more specifically, jt = 3 means
16363!! that the data are for the reference temperature tref for this pressure
16364!! level, jt = 2 refers to the temperature tref-15, jt = 1 is for
16365!! tref-30, jt = 4 is for tref+15, and jt = 5 is for tref+30.
16366!! the second index, jp, runs from 13 to 59 and refers to the jpth
16367!! reference pressure level (see taumol.f for the value of these
16368!! pressure levels in mb). the third index, ig, goes from 1 to 2,
16369!! and tells us which g-interval the absorption coefficients are for.
16370 real (kind=kind_phys), public :: absb(msb22,ng22)
16371
16372!> the array selfref contains the coefficient of the water vapor
16373!! self-continuum (including the energy term). the first index
16374!! refers to temperature in 7.2 degree increments. for instance,
16375!! jt = 1 refers to a temperature of 245.6, jt = 2 refers to 252.8,
16376!! etc. the second index runs over the g-channel (1 to 2).
16377 real (kind=kind_phys), public :: selfref(msf22,ng22)

16785 real (kind=kind_phys), public :: forref(mfr23,ng23)
16786
16787!> the array absa(65,NG23) (ka(5,13,NG23)) contains absorption coefs at
16788!! the 16 chosen g-values for a range of pressure levels> ~100mb,
16789!! temperatures, and binary species parameters (see taumol.f for definition).
16790!! the first index in the array, js, runs from 1 to 9, and corresponds to
16791!! different values of the binary species parameter. for instance,
16792!! js=1 refers to dry air, js = 2 corresponds to the paramter value 1/8,
16793!! js = 3 corresponds to the parameter value 2/8, etc. the second index
16794!! in the array, jt, which runs from 1 to 5, corresponds to different
16795!! temperatures. more specifically, jt = 3 means that the data are for
16796!! the reference temperature tref for this pressure level, jt = 2 refers
16797!! to tref-15, jt = 1 is for tref-30, jt = 4 is for tref+15, and jt = 5
16798!! is for tref+30. the third index, jp, runs from 1 to 13 and refers
16799!! to the jpth reference pressure level (see taumol.f for these levels
16800!! in mb). the fourth index, ig, goes from 1 to 10, and indicates
16801!! which g-interval the absorption coefficients are for.
16802 real (kind=kind_phys), public :: absa(msa23,ng23)
16803
16804!> the array selfref contains the coefficient of the water vapor
16805!! self-continuum (including the energy term). the first index
16806!! refers to temperature in 7.2 degree increments. for instance,
16807!! jt = 1 refers to a temperature of 245.6, jt = 2 refers to 252.8,
16808!! etc. the second index runs over the g-channel (1 to 10).
16809 real (kind=kind_phys), public :: selfref(msf23,ng23)

17046
17047 real (kind=kind_phys), public :: forref(mfr24,ng24)
17048
17049!> the array absa(585,NG24) (ka(9,5,13,NG24)) contains absorption coefs at
17050!! the 16 chosen g-values for a range of pressure levels> ~100mb,
17051!! temperatures, and binary species parameters (see taumol.f for definition).
17052!! the first index in the array, js, runs from 1 to 9, and corresponds to
17053!! different values of the binary species parameter. for instance,
17054!! js=1 refers to dry air, js = 2 corresponds to the paramter value 1/8,
17055!! js = 3 corresponds to the parameter value 2/8, etc. the second index
17056!! in the array, jt, which runs from 1 to 5, corresponds to different
17057!! temperatures. more specifically, jt = 3 means that the data are for
17058!! the reference temperature tref for this pressure level, jt = 2 refers
17059!! to tref-15, jt = 1 is for tref-30, jt = 4 is for tref+15, and jt = 5
17060!! is for tref+30. the third index, jp, runs from 1 to 13 and refers
17061!! to the jpth reference pressure level (see taumol.f for these levels
17062!! in mb). the fourth index, ig, goes from 1 to 8, and indicates
17063!! which g-interval the absorption coefficients are for.
17064 real (kind=kind_phys), public :: absa(msa24,ng24)
17065
17066!> the array absb(235,8) (kb(5,13:59,8)) contains absorption coefs at
17067!! the 16 chosen g-values for a range of pressure levels < ~100mb and
17068!! temperatures. the first index in the array, jt, which runs from 1 to 5,
17069!! corresponds to different temperatures. more specifically, jt = 3 means
17070!! that the data are for the reference temperature tref for this pressure
17071!! level, jt = 2 refers to the temperature tref-15, jt = 1 is for
17072!! tref-30, jt = 4 is for tref+15, and jt = 5 is for tref+30.
17073!! the second index, jp, runs from 13 to 59 and refers to the jpth
17074!! reference pressure level (see taumol.f for the value of these
17075!! pressure levels in mb). the third index, ig, goes from 1 to 8,
17076!! and tells us which g-interval the absorption coefficients are for.
17077 real (kind=kind_phys), public :: absb(msb24,ng24)
17078
17079!> the array selfref contains the coefficient of the water vapor
17080!! self-continuum (including the energy term). the first index
17081!! refers to temperature in 7.2 degree increments. for instance,
17082!! jt = 1 refers to a temperature of 245.6, jt = 2 refers to 252.8,
17083!! etc. the second index runs over the g-channel (1 to 8).

18121
18122! the array iabsb(235,8) (kb(5,13:59,8)) contains absorption coefs at
18123! the 16 chosen g-values for a range of pressure levels < ~100mb and
18124! temperatures. the first index in the array, jt, which runs from 1 to 5,
18125! corresponds to different temperatures. more specifically, jt = 3 means
18126! that the data are for the reference temperature tref for this pressure
18127! level, jt = 2 refers to the temperature tref-15, jt = 1 is for
18128! tref-30, jt = 4 is for tref+15, and jt = 5 is for tref+30.
18129! the second index, jp, runs from 13 to 59 and refers to the jpth
18130! reference pressure level (see taumol.f for the value of these
18131! pressure levels in mb). the third index, ig, goes from 1 to 8,
18132! and tells us which g-interval the absorption coefficients are for.

18601 parameter(msa25=65)
18602
18603!> the array absa(65,NG25) (ka(5,13,NG25)) contains absorption coefs at
18604!! the 16 chosen g-values for a range of pressure levels> ~100mb,
18605!! temperatures, and binary species parameters (see taumol.f for definition).
18606!! the first index in the array, js, runs from 1 to 9, and corresponds to
18607!! different values of the binary species parameter. for instance,
18608!! js=1 refers to dry air, js = 2 corresponds to the paramter value 1/8,
18609!! js = 3 corresponds to the parameter value 2/8, etc. the second index
18610!! in the array, jt, which runs from 1 to 5, corresponds to different
18611!! temperatures. more specifically, jt = 3 means that the data are for
18612!! the reference temperature tref for this pressure level, jt = 2 refers
18613!! to tref-15, jt = 1 is for tref-30, jt = 4 is for tref+15, and jt = 5
18614!! is for tref+30. the third index, jp, runs from 1 to 13 and refers
18615!! to the jpth reference pressure level (see taumol.f for these levels
18616!! in mb). the fourth index, ig, goes from 1 to 6, and indicates
18617!! which g-interval the absorption coefficients are for.
18618 real (kind=kind_phys), public :: absa(msa25,ng25)

19401 integer, public :: msb28
19402 parameter(msa28=585, msb28=1175)
19403
19404
19405!> the array absa(585,NG28) (ka((9,5,13,NG28)) contains absorption coefs at
19406!! the 16 chosen g-values for a range of pressure levels> ~100mb,
19407!! temperatures, and binary species parameters (see taumol.f for definition).
19408!! the first index in the array, js, runs from 1 to 9, and corresponds to
19409!! different values of the binary species parameter. for instance,
19410!! js=1 refers to dry air, js = 2 corresponds to the paramter value 1/8,
19411!! js = 3 corresponds to the parameter value 2/8, etc. the second index
19412!! in the array, jt, which runs from 1 to 5, corresponds to different
19413!! temperatures. more specifically, jt = 3 means that the data are for
19414!! the reference temperature tref for this pressure level, jt = 2 refers
19415!! to tref-15, jt = 1 is for tref-30, jt = 4 is for tref+15, and jt = 5
19416!! is for tref+30. the third index, jp, runs from 1 to 13 and refers
19417!! to the jpth reference pressure level (see taumol.f for these levels
19418!! in mb). the fourth index, ig, goes from 1 to 6, and indicates
19419!! which g-interval the absorption coefficients are for.
19420 real (kind=kind_phys), public :: absa(msa28,ng28)
19421
19422!> the array absb(1175,6) (kb(5,5,13:59,6)) contains absorption coefs at
19423!! the 16 chosen g-values for a range of pressure levels < ~100mb and
19424!! temperatures. the first index in the array, jt, which runs from 1 to 5,
19425!! corresponds to different temperatures. more specifically, jt = 3 means
19426!! that the data are for the reference temperature tref for this pressure
19427!! level, jt = 2 refers to the temperature tref-15, jt = 1 is for
19428!! tref-30, jt = 4 is for tref+15, and jt = 5 is for tref+30.
19429!! the second index, jp, runs from 13 to 59 and refers to the jpth
19430!! reference pressure level (see taumol.f for the value of these
19431!! pressure levels in mb). the third index, ig, goes from 1 to 6,
19432!! and tells us which g-interval the absorption coefficients are for.
19433 real (kind=kind_phys), public :: absb(msb28,ng28)
19434
19435!> rayleigh extinction coefficient
19436 real (kind=kind_phys), parameter, public :: rayl = 2.02e-05

21717 integer, public :: msf29

21719 integer, public :: mfr29
21720 parameter(msa29=65, msb29=235, msf29=10, mfr29=4)
21721
21722 real (kind=kind_phys), public :: forref(mfr29,ng29)
21723
21724!> the array absa(65,NG29) (ka(5,13,NG29)) contains absorption coefs at
21725!! the 16 chosen g-values for a range of pressure levels> ~100mb,
21726!! temperatures, and binary species parameters (see taumol.f for definition).
21727!! the first index in the array, js, runs from 1 to 9, and corresponds to
21728!! different values of the binary species parameter. for instance,
21729!! js=1 refers to dry air, js = 2 corresponds to the paramter value 1/8,
21730!! js = 3 corresponds to the parameter value 2/8, etc. the second index
21731!! in the array, jt, which runs from 1 to 5, corresponds to different
21732!! temperatures. more specifically, jt = 3 means that the data are for
21733!! the reference temperature tref for this pressure level, jt = 2 refers
21734!! to tref-15, jt = 1 is for tref-30, jt = 4 is for tref+15, and jt = 5
21735!! is for tref+30. the third index, jp, runs from 1 to 13 and refers
21736!! to the jpth reference pressure level (see taumol.f for these levels
21737!! in mb). the fourth index, ig, goes from 1 to 12, and indicates
21738!! which g-interval the absorption coefficients are for.
21739 real (kind=kind_phys), public :: absa(msa29,ng29)
21740
21741!> the array absb(235,12) (kb(5,13:59,12)) contains absorption coefs at
21742!! the 16 chosen g-values for a range of pressure levels < ~100mb and
21743!! temperatures. the first index in the array, jt, which runs from 1 to 5,
21744!! corresponds to different temperatures. more specifically, jt = 3 means
21745!! that the data are for the reference temperature tref for this pressure
21746!! level, jt = 2 refers to the temperature tref-15, jt = 1 is for
21747!! tref-30, jt = 4 is for tref+15, and jt = 5 is for tref+30.
21748!! the second index, jp, runs from 13 to 59 and refers to the jpth
21749!! reference pressure level (see taumol.f for the value of these
21750!! pressure levels in mb). the third index, ig, goes from 1 to 12,
21751!! and tells us which g-interval the absorption coefficients are for.
21752 real (kind=kind_phys), public :: absb(msb29,ng29)
21753
21754!> the array selfref contains the coefficient of the water vapor
21755!! self-continuum (including the energy term). the first index
21756!! refers to temperature in 7.2 degree increments. For instance,
21757!! jt = 1 refers to a temperature of 245.6, jt = 2 refers to 252.8,
21758!! etc. the second index runs over the g-channel (1 to 12).
21759 real (kind=kind_phys), public :: selfref(msf29,ng29)

21959
21960! the array absb(235,12) (kb(5,13:59,12)) contains absorption coefs at
21961! the 16 chosen g-values for a range of pressure levels < ~100mb and
21962! temperatures. the first index in the array, jt, which runs from 1 to 5,
21963! corresponds to different temperatures. more specifically, jt = 3 means
21964! that the data are for the reference temperature tref for this pressure
21965! level, jt = 2 refers to the temperature tref-15, jt = 1 is for
21966! tref-30, jt = 4 is for tref+15, and jt = 5 is for tref+30.
21967! the second index, jp, runs from 13 to 59 and refers to the jpth
21968! reference pressure level (see taumol.f for the value of these
21969! pressure levels in mb). the third index, ig, goes from 1 to 12,
21970! and tells us which g-interval the absorption coefficients are for.
